  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The COVID-19 Open Research Dataset (CORD-19) has garnered significant academic interest, evidenced by 4 citations in various reputable venues, including bioRxiv and the Journal of Medical Internet Research. Hosted on Zenodo, this dataset has been viewed over 20,110 times and downloaded 16,310 times, showcasing its crucial role in enabling further research during the pandemic.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The COVID-19 Open Research Dataset (CORD-19), created by authors Sebastian Kohlmeier, Kyle Lo, Lucy Lu Wang, and J-J. Yang from the Allen Institute, represents a significant effort to facilitate research related to the COVID-19 pandemic. Hosted on Zenodo, this dataset has achieved notable visibility with a total of 20,110 views and 16,310 downloads, underscoring its value to the research community and its accessibility for further exploration of COVID-19 related topics.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The engagement with this dataset illustrates a commitment to open science principles, as it has been shared early in its development. This early sharing reflects the authors' intent to enable rapid access to critical information, vital in the fast-evolving landscape of COVID-19 research. Despite having no formal citations or mentions in social media platforms, the dataset's academic footprint is reinforced by its citations in prominent outlets such as bioRxiv and the Journal of Medical Internet Research, indicating its integration into the scholarly discourse on COVID-19.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset facilitates proven downstream reuse, with 4 instances of other researchers building upon its findings. This points to its effectiveness as a foundational research output, providing essential data for subsequent studies aimed at understanding and combating the impacts of COVID-19. The authors' collaboration with a key institution, the Allen Institute, further strengthens its scientific credibility and relevance.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In summary, the COVID-19 Open Research Dataset stands out not only for its empirical metrics but also for its role in enhancing collaboration across disciplines. As researchers continue to explore the implications of this unprecedented pandemic, datasets like CORD-19 serve as invaluable resources, fostering an environment where knowledge and data are shared freely and efficiently for the greater good of society.</p>",
